Interface LinkedList<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of the elements to store in the linked list
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    SinglyLinkedList

    public interface LinkedList<E>
    The LinkedList interface defines a set of standard operations that are typically associated with linked list, such as adding, removing, and checking to see if the list contains an item. Note that while your linked list implementation should make use of a Node class, the methods below take in and return instances of the generic type, not the nodes themselves.

    • Method Detail

      • get

        E get(int index)
        Returns the element in the linked list at the specified index. Does not change the contents of the list in any way. If the given index is negative or greater than the maximum possible index, returns null.
        Parameters:
        index - of element to be retrieved
        Returns:
        the element at the given index or null if index out of bounds

      • add

        void add(E data)
        Adds the specified piece of data to the end of the linked list. This method should execute in O(1) (constant) time. This means that you should not iterate over the whole list to add the item to the end (we will check for this).
        Parameters:
        data - the object to be added to the linked list

      • add

        boolean add(int index,
            E data)
        Adds given piece of data to the linked list at the given index. All items that were originally at the index or after the index should be shifted down by one. If the index specified is not valid, returns false. Otherwise, returns true. If the index specified is 0 or if it is one larger than the maximum current index (ie if index is equal to the size of the linked list), then this method should execute in O(1) (constant) time. This means that you should not iterate over the entire list to add the element, as it is unnecessary to do so.
        Parameters:
        index - the index at which to add the item
        data - the item to be added to te linked list
        Returns:
        true if the data could be added at the given index

      • addAll

        void addAll(java.util.Collection<? extends E> c)
        Adds each element in the Collection to the end of the linked list.
        Parameters:
        c - the collection of items to add to the end of the linked list

      • contains

        boolean contains(E data)
        Determines whether or not the given piece of data is in the linked list.
        Parameters:
        data - the item to check
        Returns:
        true if the linked list contains the item, false otherwise

      • containsAll

        boolean containsAll(java.util.Collection<? extends E> c)
        Determines whether or not every element of the given Collection is in the linked list.
        Parameters:
        c - the Collection of elements to check
        Returns:
        true if list contains every element in the Collection

      • remove

        boolean remove(E data)
        Finds the first element of the list equal to the given piece of data and removes it from the list. Returns false if the given piece of data is not in the list and therefore cannot be removed.
        Parameters:
        data - the piece of data to be removed from the list
        Returns:
        true if the item was removed, false if list does not contain it

      • remove

        E remove(int index)
        Removes and returns the item in the list at the given index. All items at indices after the given index are shifted down by one.
        Parameters:
        index - the index of the item to remove from the linked list
        Returns:
        the removed item

      • removeAll

        boolean removeAll(java.util.Collection<? extends E> c)
        Removes each element in the given collection from the linked list.
        Parameters:
        c - the Collection of items to remove
        Returns:
        true if each element in the Collection was removed.

      • size

        int size()
        Returns the number of elements in the linked list. This method should execute in O(1) (constant) time. This means that you should not iterate over the entire list to count the number of items, but rather you should maintain a size variable that you can just return here.
        Returns:
        the number of elements in the linked list

      • isEmpty

        boolean isEmpty()
        Returns true if the linked list has no elements.
        Returns:
        true if the list is empty, false otherwise

      • clear

        void clear()
        Removes all elements from the list. After calling this method, the isEmpty method should return true.
